The first virtual operator is already arriving this year in the Czech Republic.
Probably.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer almost all services as their Western European partners.
However, here we still lack something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
It's probably not gonna be long.
That Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have already written it in mobile.cz.
The rest was also confirmed by the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ) which warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is among the most expensive in the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulating roaming rates it is likely to reach a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators the SMS that send them from abroad will be cheaper than if they send them from home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, lacks competition that you really want to fight.
This probably seems paradoxical to us, because we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that there is extreme competition in the Czech market.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTU), Pavel Dvořák, has already said that there is no place in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It is perhaps true that for a classic operator with his own network he no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be very difficult to find some frequency).
However, there is still a possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market brought a sharp drop in prices to which classic operators had to react as well.
At the same time, even before the entry of sharks such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile into Britain's market, similar voices were heard both there and here.
It has been shown that there is room for this type of operator and that they can succeed.
Otherwise, you don't have to look for examples too far away.
In February this year we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
Only after half a year, this operator managed to obtain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighbouring country.
On the other hand, after Mobilking there is the Penta group which, apart from that, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of concentrating on many more specific target groups.
In addition, in order to be able to function effectively, they need many fewer customers than a classic operator.
They do not carry relatively large costs in the construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world this type of virtual operators usually profile with low costs - they offer cheap calls and SMS messages that however, they often counteract with the supply of more adjusted services.
Thus, for example, Tesco mobile in Britain offers SMS at least half of the cheap compared to the competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can be a good hit also the bet for a trivial nothing target group.
This operator specifically addresses man.
"The right man chooses Mobilking - he is the operator that likes and who can be trusted," says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, who works this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether such a concept as that of Poland could tie up in our country.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav Čepický doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
Moreover from the point of view of the provision of services is relatively saturated"
In the Czech Republic there is no possibility, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if in the Czech Republic there will be any virtual operator that will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the Czech Republic does not seem too hopeful.
Rather, it is about the launch of Mobilking in other countries in our region," he said in telephone conversation for mobile.cz, Jana Studničková, spokesman for the Penta financial group.
Indirectly he assured that the current mobile telephone operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not inclined to this idea.
Rather, they try to do everything possible to ensure that no potential competition arises.
Interest in the launch of a virtual mobile operator is already shown by the GTS Novera group that would like to take a step forward to become a real competition of Telefónica O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in this, so that we can offer our customers not only fixed telephony services but also mobile telephony services.
And the sooner, the better.
With this possibility we have met repeatedly with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them we have made progress in the meetings," said the group spokesman, Pavel Kaidl.
Then maybe they'll spark better times.
It seems that, for unofficial information, the first official operator would likely have to arrive by the end of the year.
But for now its appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment we believe that the situation is suitable for the emergence of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
So far no one has addressed us with any complex and serious project in this field," he said for mobil.cz, Vlastimil Sršeÿ, spokesman for Telefónica O2.
Other operators refer to the specific nature of the Czech market.
T-mobile spokesman Martina Kemrová, in exceptional compliance with O2's opinion, adds: "To this day we have not recorded any viable commercial projects that, bilaterally beneficial, can continue to develop."
He adds: "In the T-Mobile network it will be difficult to find a virtual operator until the end of the year.
At this moment we should already have on the table some specific contract that could be studied on such a short horizon."
Vodafone focuses rather on meeting the requirements of a 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this with regard to the sharing of costs and infrastructure.
Precisely, we consider it to be the biggest contribution from the point of view of customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this field is in the partner with whom to establish a shared network for a fast internet on the mobile."
Responsible offices - with the operators nail and meat
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increasing competition which would lead to lower prices and thus lower profits.
Then why facilitate entry into competition?
When operators want to get something, they are able to pull from the same rope, proof of it is the grip when U:fon arose.
Perhaps the greatest pressure on the ČTU was at the time of U:fon's entry by T-Mobile society.
Public information accessible on the ČTÚ websites attests to this.
But precisely now U:fon serves as an argument why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds to this: "In addition, the competitive environment in the mobile phone market has not long been open to a fourth operator.
With regard to the character of the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic it is natural that the entry of another player into the market would mean for him and, above all, for his services great requirements."
This is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously discouraging because of the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
This is not just the position of the ČTU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in commercial tenders, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
This belongs purely to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Licenses (UOHS).
However, it expressed its typical position on this issue.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile phone market would be possible after an agreement on the rental of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile operator and a virtual operator was concluded.
To date, no agreements have been concluded since the offer of the potentials interested rather was not interesting enough for the classic operators", added our question Kristián Chalupa, of the UOHS Department of External Relations.
These statements do not surprise the representatives of the operators.
For the offices that must represent the interests of consumers, this is more than just a consideration, apart from that they must note that no one takes advantage of their position on the market.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "In the foreign country where virtual operators operate normally we can observe that their entry into the market contributed to the fall in prices of mobile phone services"
Clearly, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market and the fall in prices does not fall within the interest of UOHS.
Indeed, the dramatic shock in all of this case lies in the dissonant reactions resulting from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether it really is a coincidence, is offered on its own.
It is the same as with the price of gasoline in gas stations because it is clear that it is the work of chance and of a hard struggle for competition.
"The Office in this regard has found no signs of unfair competition and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position and therefore do not have a corresponding increase of responsibility in their market performance.
The tools needed to open the mobile phone market to virtual operators, rather, are missing, as well as telecommunications regulators," he added to his Chalupa response.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of the many conflicting points.
There is obviously an analysis of relevant markets developed by the ČTU that telecommunications is from the point of view of commercial tendering a single market.
In this type of market naturally none of the Czech operators have a dominant position.
However some of the legal experts offer another vision - for a virtual operator to emerge is always necessary the agreement with the network administrator.
And the mobile phone operator - with all its logic - has the monopoly of its network.
Therefore, in a particular segment it must necessarily be dominant.
And if this argument was not accepted, at least for UOHS it should be a warning that three mobile operators are strikingly rising similarly.
The current complaints of the stakeholders (inluded by GTS Novera) show that in all negotiations with the operators they clash with many similar impediments.
Loading responsibility in the ČTú is a fairly common trick in the field of telecommunications of which the UOHS washes its hands in this whole matter.
We've met him already in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, a new amendment to the telecommunications law was recently introduced to extend the competence of the ČTU in the field of commercial tenders that did not take place, even though a number of specialists promised that the situation would improve.
This must be perfectly known by UOHS representatives, but it is clear that their interests are elsewhere.
It's all right, when no one looks
At the same time, something like a pseudovirtual operator that already exists in Czech mobile networks remains unnoticed.
They are companies that put their own prices on mobile phone services that, however, only a part are public.
These are usually multi-level marketing companies.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
Usually only some elected get the price list of these companies.
The magic is in which the company, with respect to the operator, acts as a classic business customer of the same ordering a large number of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will then receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that commercial conditions in all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If cases such as those cited could be found to be in breach of the terms of the contract that could be translated at the end of the collaboration with the given society," answered the question about this problem Martina Kemrová.
But it is quite unlikely that an activity of this kind carried out by mobile operators would not reach responsible people.
It is precisely in the case of the three companies mentioned above that thousands of customers can become involved.
None of the operators are against this procedure.
With the activities of these companies they gain nothing despicable and, at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns us of the possible problems: "the law allows such speculation, however, the services of this company are used only by a despicable so many percent of customers.
These, moreover, must accept that your phone's SIM card is not in your name so that they cannot absolutely dispose of it as a normal customer of the operators."
Precisely this is what should seem to the minimally strange ČTU.
There is also a new question for UOHS.
If mobile phone operators turn their eyes on this type of procedure, why block the entry of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that UOHS has sufficient competence to discover this type of activity and if it is not going to want to be satisfied with the operators' explanations that they have no idea of this history and that their commercial conditions do not allow it.
When we stop being the most expensive
As has already been clear in the text, the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market has led to a significant decrease in service prices.
At the same time, in virtually all the countries where the virtual operator emerged, classical operators tried more or less to protect themselves from this break-in.
The arguments used by these were virtually all identical - too small, a market, eventually, too saturated, problems with the quality of service, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, regulatory bodies have now intervened and in none of the cases have defended operators but their customers.
Whether with formal measures or informal pressure, the first virtual operator emerged and others began to emerge with it.
Unfortunately, the Czech Regulatory Authority this whole case happens as if it were a burning nail.
From our experience we cannot fail to impress that the confusion of powers in these cases suits them.
But let's not despair.
If this background information is correct and the virtual operator actually reaches these lands, then the Czech mobile phone market is likely to start moving again.
If any of the operators lets any virtual mobile operator in, it will be difficult for UOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And we may stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four presentations of the new version of the Czech official anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek on the occasion of the day of the Czech official celebrations presented the new official recording of the anthem Where, my home.
The new anthem was recorded by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - two versions that are Solos, one with a male voice and one with a female voice, another with a Choir and another instrumental.
Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka are in charge of the song.
The authors of the anthem arrangements are Otakar Jeremiah and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz server you can listen to the four versions.
Bělohlávek considers this Czech national song one of the most beautiful hymns.
The Czech Radio has already said before that it intentionally chose for the Solos singers with voices representatively young who are more expressive and popular.
"From the beginning I have tried with both of them and then, also, with the Choir that were fixed in the diction so that the text would be well understood, so that it would be aligned," he said.
The Czech official anthem celebrates its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Where, my Home sounded for the first time in 1834 on the tables of the State Theatre in the original Czech work Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl and arranged with the music of František Škroup.
It gained popularity and people made it theirs.
The first stanza of the song after the emergence of Czechoslovakia in 1918 became, naturally, a part of the official anthem.
One of the seven official symbols remained even after the emergence of the independent Czech Republic.
