The MHD of Prague takes us on Wednesday for the first time with the chip
On Wednesday, October 1, 2008, the Prague Transport Company's history describes the date when the first passengers enter the metro, tram and bus with an electronic ticket in their pockets instead of a paper ticket.
This can be purchased right now by almost a hundred thousand people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can buy the 30-day, 90-day and annual voucher (this will be valid from 1 January 2009) and simultaneously load it on their chip card at the infocentres and posts of the transport company at the stations of Metro, Muzeum, Městek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letñany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
Bonuses can be purchased from yesterday on the Internet on the transport company's pages, www.dpp.cz.
The service, until the afternoon, was used by more than four hundred people.
Those who start using the Internet as a form of commerce can definitely start forgetting the ticket sales posts at the subway stations, where so far they should regularly queue up to take out a normal ticket.
The bonus is purchased online, and the Opencard card will be charged to you in one of the thirteen branches of the Municipal Library.
"In these places there is at the disposal of the passengers a window with prepared staff that helps interested people with the internet purchase and also with the charging of the voucher purchased on their card," said the project spokesman, Martin Opartrný.
Apart from the library, it will also be possible to reload the electronic bonus on the Opencard in the vending machines that are located in some metro halls.
What are these vending machines like?
They are red, they remind us of a ticket picker and the travelers will probably have already fixed themselves on them at the stations of the metro of Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There is now in the city five but by the end of the year there would have to be eighty," Opatrný completed.
The bonus is controlled by the machine instead of the driver
The use of the machine, which will start working tomorrow, is simple.
Simply insert the Opencard chip card into it and the previously paid bonus will be charged only on it.
Electronic bonds from tomorrow are valid not only in the capital but also in its surroundings.
In other words, on the surrounding trains and bus lines from the numbers 300 to 499 that mainly use the inhabitants of the localities of Central Bohemia.
"In the trains attached to the integrated transport of Prague there are reviewers equipped with a reading card that will help confirm the validity of the time and the area of the bonus," explained the check of the tickets, Filip Drápal of the organization Ropid that establishes the schedules of the collective transport of Prague.
Circumval buses have their reading cards mounted in the driver's locker.
When entering it is necessary not only to show the card to the driver but also it is necessary to accompany it with the Opencard in the place intended for it on the side of the Box.
With this, the driver controls the validity of the bonus.
"If the passenger needs to verify the validity of the bonds there is nothing easier than asking the driver for this information," Drápal completed.
Passengers who don't travel on the bypass buses and don't remember when the bonus ends can go to the vending machines where the cards are recharged.
Here, on the machine screen, you will be shown information about the validity of your document.
