The interview - Blood is safe again
Hema-Québec celebrated yesterday its 10th anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, because Hema-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, he regained the confidence of the public that had seriously been wavered by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated by Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this drama and public discontent, the Government of Canada conducted a public survey in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horacio Krever, which sought to clarify the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations for such a disaster not to recur.
While Judge Krever was late to present his relationship, certain provinces then created a committee that aimed to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gelineau Committee carried out this mission.
As a result of the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Hema-Québec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and territories.
" In 1998, when Hema-Québec began its activities, almost 38% of the people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, recalls Decary.
The situation was disappointing.
Having made a lot of efforts to improve the safety of blood products and a lot of work during the years that followed, we have regained public confidence," he says before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the population of Quebec now had confidence in Hema-Québec.
Dr. Decary nevertheless recalls that "confidence is extremely fragile. "
Since its creation, on September 28, 1998, Hema-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, we were witnessing in Europe the birth of numerous cases of the human variant of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says Decary.
And we didn't know if this disease could be transmitted by blood.
We then rely on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which when we do not know it and when a serious illness can arise from it, in this case the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that is characterized by a brain degeneration that inevitably leads to death, we introduce exclusion measures.
In April 1999, we denied the blood of those who had stayed more than a month in the United Kingdom since 1980.
But a few years ago, it has been demonstrated beyond any doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode thus showed us that the precautionary principle that was applied had meaning. "
In 1999, a much more sensitive HIV detection technique appeared on the market: nucleid acid tests that allow for the direct detection of the presence of the virus in the donor's blood and not of antibodies to the virus, based on the tests used so far.
Nucleid acid tests allowed the period between the time the person has been infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
We could reduce this period by less than a week.
We therefore substantially reduce the risk that certain donors will be infected without knowing it and that we will not be able to detect them.
These improvements significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through blood transfusions.
Today, one person every 12 million is at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
"That means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
As Hema-Québec distributes between 400 000 and 500 000 blood products each year, more than 24 years will pass before a case of transmission of HIV by a blood product occurs.
I think you can now receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to recover health without worries," says the head of the management of Hema-Québec.
" Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
It is never known which pathogen could emerge in the system.
Last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant," Dr. Décary says before stressing that in addition to safe supplies, Hema-Québec must also provide sufficient supplies.
" Needs increase because the population ages.
Since the most aggressive anticancer treatments, patients often need a red blood cell or platelet injection.
The ageing of the population also has consequences on the network of blood donors that groups on average only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation. "
All people with good health, aged 18 and who meet the eligibility criteria, however, can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who propose their blood are not accepted, because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they travel to a country where malaria reigns, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
" With this 3%, we manage to maintain an inventory that covers the needs of hospitals.
The hardships are very rare.
But we must renew the members of this network of donors as they age and can no longer donate their blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to retain them and encourage them to be regular donors.
Since the present life is very unbridled, we rarely find time to spend an hour donating his blood, " says Francine Decary.
With a budget of $297 million annually, Hema-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public blood bank of the umbilical cord in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was formerly considered as biomedical waste is filled with a blood rich in stem cells that can be used for the treatment of serious diseases such as leukemia.
" We celebrated a few weeks ago, putting on the bench our thousandth sample of blood from the umbilical cord and are expected to take out more than a thousand of these per year.
We would have to start proposing it for grafts at the beginning of next year, " says Dr. Décary, who describes this very popular cord blood collection program.
" Many mothers are disappointed to be unable to enjoy this, " since Hema-Québec has no resources to propose this complex and expensive program in all Quebec hospitals.
