Psychology of Overlays: Why do we spend more money?
Auction participants are likely to spend more money and overvalue the product.
Neurologists and economists at the University of New York discovered the neurological - economic bases of this known and apparently irrational behavior.
According to the study in Science magazine, people do not want to lose in skills like eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay even an excessive price.
Scientists tried to establish the neurological scheme of this "game" by means of experimental auctions.
One of the volunteer groups played lottery, the other participated in an auction and in the meantime was examined through the functional magnetic resonance system (fMRI) the active areas of the brain of the people participating in the experiment.
In both games participants could earn money, but during the auctions, where it is essential to bet more than the other, when losing the game intensified the operation of the complex called stratum located under the cerebral cortex.
This area of the brain, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the "self-prime" mechanism of the nervous system.
Thus, according to scientists, the increase in bets is explained as a prevention in order not to provoke an intense reaction of the stratum.
To substantiate their theory, the economists of the scientific group also carried out a financial follow-up study.
In this experiment three groups bet against one person under different circumstances.
The control group was simply informed of the actual value of the product in question, and its members bet.
In addition to this, another group was promised that if they win, they would receive $15 more prize.
On the other hand, the third group received exactly $15 before the auction, but in the event of losing the auction, the members of the group even lost that money.
Thus the only difference between the two groups was that for one the triumph was highlighted and for the other the failure.
However, by checking the hypothesis of neurologists, the members of the group playing "against failure" were willing to bet even more than the members of the control group and the "winner" group.
"These results cannot be deduced from any previous economic theory.
For those so far explained the phenomena of auctions only with the joy of winning and with the prevention of risks.
Only visual neurological methods helped to resolve this contradiction between the two theories, so we now come to a third explanation" - Andrew Schotter, professor of the University of New York's Faculty of Economics, established.
Hepatitis: When should you go to your doctor?
Around the world some 500 million people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary chronic liver disease is considered one of the main causes of death.
The number of infected people in this country is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated as many of the sick do not know that they are infected.
The name of hepatitis is the common name of different liver diseases caused by viruses.
Symptoms are very similar; liver and jaundice infection are characteristic, but their pathogens and diseases are very different.
Hepatitis viruses dependent on the pathogen are spread through two main forms: hepatitis A and E via food (e.g. with water or contaminated food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body moods (sperm, vagina humor, saliva).
It is advisable for travellers to protect themselves by means of A and B vaccines, against C, there are no vaccines.
The symptoms of hepatitis A occur two or three weeks after consuming the infected food, manifest by a general condition, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After that, the jaundice, the excrement becomes clear, the dark-colored urine and healing can last for even two to three weeks.
A million people die in cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B, the most serious forms of this disease every year in the world.
The main reason for this is that, according to the calculations, only one in ten infected patients receive pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: without treatment it can cause liver cirrhosis and even cancer.
Most people who are infected do not know that they are sick because this pathological agent gradually destroys liver cells and often the first symptoms only appear 20-30 years later.
Therefore, premature recognition, systematic medical control, is very important.
This disease is much more common in three groups: people who had blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and those with tattoos.
There are currently some 200 million people in the world suffering from chronic hepatitis C.
As this disease can be discovered with routine laboratory control too, it is worth consulting with the family doctor when experiencing some unknown symptom.
The disease has healing if it is discovered in time, it is possible to exterminate the virus from the body, so it can suppress the contagion and prevent cancer.
September 30 is the World Hepatitis Day, which was organized for the first time in 2004 by organizations representing the sick.
Its aim is to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by viruses and the importance of their early recognition.
Does it hurt less who believe in God?
According to the result of a recent investigation, religious faith had a calming effect that also alleviated the death of the martyrs of Catholicism.
Scientists at Oxford University carried out an interesting experiment: they analyzed that religious belief in how it influences human pain - reported the British newspaper Telegraph.
As part of this unique experiment, 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists were subjected to electric shock, while all were looking at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude most of their pain.
Thanks to the human brain scanning technique, it could be verified that Catholic believers were able to activate that part of their brain that is responsible for the regulation of pain.
This experiment is the first in the series of research in which scientists, philosophers and theologians from the various departments of the University also participate alongside academics.
The analysis was done as follows; they fixed a chipping instrument to the patient's left hand, which applied the electric shock.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to fix their gaze in two paintings; the Virgin Mary, work of Sassoferrato of the 17th century and the Lady of the arm of Leonardo da Vinci of the 15th century.
The researchers had the hope that the Virgin Mary's spectacle would provoke a certain religious spirit among the faithful, while they chose Leonardo's oil because it was not too different from the other, and thought it had reassuring effect.
The patients spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, receiving 20 electric shocks in four successive parts during that period while watching religious or other subject painting.
The Catholics claimed that when they looked at the Virgin Mary they felt "security" as "protected" people, "were reassured and peace reigned in their hearts."
When observing the religious theme picture, they felt 12 percent less pain than when they looked at Leonardo's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the experiment, thinks that with any such impacting image you can achieve a similar effect with atheists too, you just have to find the right image.
"We should find the portrait of a person for whom they feel very positively, as by a mother or a father," said the psychologist.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright celebrated the outcome of the investigation.
"The exercise of faith should and in many cases really change our personality" - Wright added.
After these wonderful results there is only one question: what effect would it have on the regulation of pain if the faithful were shown the Madonna of Leonardo or another painter of her size?
Would the vision of a high-quality Virgin Mary yield even better results?
