The smart car mimics the flight of the bunny
What would be the best method to develop technologies in order to avoid collisions, if not imitation of existing obstacles sensors in nature?
For example, that of the bumblebees.
In an amazing project presented at CETEC in Japan, the billboards gave the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision prevention systems.
The Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the BR23C imitating car robotics management system of nature, to which they gave the characteristics of the billboards, with the ultimate objective of creating a system that can avoid all collisions.
During the flight each bunny creates its own particular oval space that actually looks a lot like our protective safety capsule - explained in the exhibition Kazuhhiro Doi, technological director of PR and development and research.
They play an important role the composite eyes of the eyelids that are able to see in all directions at an angle greater than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of composite eyes, engineers used the laser-ray length measurement system.
This identifies the obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 meters, at an angle of 180 degrees, calculates its distance and sends a signal to the vehicle microprocessor that immediately transforms into a maneuver to avoid collision.
In a fraction of seconds the obstacle is identified, then the robot of the vehicle imitating the movements of the buffs, modifies the direction by turning the wheels to the necessary extent.
Unlike any current system, this maneuver is completely instinctive.
"If not, the vehicle robot could not react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the vehicle robot project.
It must react immediately and instinctively, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the protective safety capsule, in a layer within which all types of collisions are currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what an abbey does to avoid other abbeys.
This process must be carried out in an eye-opening and closing process.
However, unlike the abbeys, the movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or diagonals, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the steering direction of the wheels
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for the buffs to avoid other buffs, here they only used as a possibility for the robot of the car the rotational movement and the acceleration in addition the braking.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and its energy density is higher, meaning that they have a longer lifespan than lithium-ion batteries.
According to Andoh, the important thing is the instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the data processing capacity, let alone the storage capacity.
This device in every second should only process some input signals and react as appropriate.
It is not necessary to store this data or react with an instinctive logic based on the data from the previous maneuvers, so it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of memory.
No memories of gigabytes, no megabytes are needed.
This is the first step to develop technology to immediately avoid obstacles, which, according to Nissan's calculations, can be incorporated into the models manufactured in series within ten years.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to his destination, avoiding the obstacles existing on his way.
