The written version of the law of the $700 billion financial rescue package has been prepared and will be applied at various stages in order to buy bad loans from banks.
Half the money will be spent in the first phase.
According to Eastern Coast time during the new consultations that lasted until after midnight on Saturday, Congress leaders reached an agreement around the $700 billion financial rescue package in total, after several days of discussion - Reuters reported.
We have achieved significant progress - said Nancy Pelosi, Democratic President of the American Congress, stating that the agreement is only to be formalized in a document.
The compromise on the package was supported by both presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain.
Henry Paulson, the Minister of Finance, speaking about the outcome of the commitment stated: this program will work and be efficient but other measures are needed more. According to Pelosi, it's not about saving the Wall Street, it's about turning the economy cart around.
The written version of the package was published before the opening of the Asian markets, i.e. Sunday before 8 p.m., according to Washington time (i.e. before 2 p.m. on Monday, according to Central Europe time), without causing a spectacular jump in the bags.
On the draft law called the emergency law for economic stabilization of 2008, the first Monday will vote for the American Congress and then the Senate.
President George W. Bush on Saturday night consulted Pelosi and then the White House also celebrated the news about the agreement.
We are pleased with the progress made during the night and highly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy - said Tony Fratto, spokesman for the White House.
The program is different from the Bush administration's original proposal to spend all $700 billion to buy bad quality credit fund securities.
Now only half of the $700 billion will be spent, using 250 billion immediately after Congress votes, probably on Monday, of this sum the Ministry of Finance will buy securities of credit, bad ratings and the fate of another $100 billion depends on the President's decision.
This programme will be controlled by a special body, in which the President of the Federal Reserve will also participate.
The other half of the $700 billion could be spent after a new Congressional decision.
According to the law, the Ministry of Finance can apply a combined tactic: it can simultaneously purchase bad loans, mortgages and credit fund securities, as well as other "venuous" credits as well.
The purchase can be made in auctions or directly - competent persons of the ministry reported.
The law allows the companies concerned to participate in an insurance program where the financial portfolio guarantees the worrying elements, for which the companies will pay the amount corresponding to the foreseeable damages.
Henry Paulson stated: the law thus ensures the necessary financial means, which can even reach up to $700 billion to meet the urgent needs of the American financial system, to deal with the purchase of bad financial means, their insurance or the prevention of risks that could lead to the collapse of some large financial institutions.
We do everything necessary to be ready to introduce the law as soon as they sign it - he added.
On the other hand, the heads of the banks that are in distress and wait for state aid will be able to count on the official limitation of their compensations, which the American slang simply calls gold parachutes.
Only in certain cases will payments be limited, and limitations depend on the form of assistance of the Ministry of Finance.
The limitation means that if the ministry buys in the framework of an auction, an extra tax will be imposed on the gold parachute, unless the failed head of the bank is jubilated.
By directly buying bad credits, the government will intervene aggressively to ensure that the chiefs' compensations are not exaggerated.
In addition to the above, existing gold parachute contracts will not be changed, the limitations refer only to new contracts to stimulate participation in the programme as well.
This is the first case in American history that will be in force a legal limitation on the revenues of the Directors General - said the Democratic Barney Frank, president of the Congressional commission, responsible for financial services.
The State will also have the right to acquire shares of the banks participating in the programme, thus reducing the risk of taxpayers, as they will ultimately be able to obtain profits with the transaction as soon as the economy recovers and with it the bank.
According to the bill over the next five years, the president will have to present to Congress a proposal on how to return the losses of the financial sector to taxpayers.
Of course, on both sides there were those who expressed their reservations about the project.
This is not what the American citizens entrusted to us, that is, they are not protecting the taxpayers' dollars - said the Republican Congressman of California, Darrell Issa.
His Ohio Democratic colleague, Mary Kaptur, said: the measures urged him the same ones who are responsible for the collapse of Wall Street.
Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent compared to last month's prices and 12.9 per cent compared to August 2007 prices - reported the Central Bureau of Statistics (KSH).
Industrial export prices rose by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008 and decreased by 3.9 per cent compared to the previous year.
As a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared to the previous month and by 3.2 per cent compared to the previous year.
Industrial sales prices rose only to a minimum of 0.1 per cent.
The domestic sales prices of the processing industry sectors increased by a minimum of 0.1 per cent over the month of July.
The largest price increase occurred in August 2008 in the leather and footwear production sector (2.8 per cent), primarily due to the 4.6 per cent monthly increase in the stock exchanges and belts and the 2.5 per cent increase in the footwear sector.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical base materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical production branch (1.6 per cent).
There was a decrease in price in the petrochemical sector, (1.4 per cent), in the production of electric machines and instruments (0.9 per cent), as well as - to a minimum - in the wood processing sectors (0.1 per cent).
They did not change the prices of paper manufacturing, editorials and printing.
In the rest of the processing industry, prices increased between 0.2 and 0.9 per cent.
In the supply of electricity, gas, heat and water representing a significant weight in domestic trade, an increase of 0.3 per cent was recorded in August, primarily as a result of the effect of the increase in official prices from 1 July.
In a comparison of a twelve-month period - in domestic sales of the processing industry sectors - the highest price increase was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4 per cent).
In the metal processing sector, an increase of 13.2 per cent was observed, while in the food, beverage and tobacco industries, which were of decisive weight, there was an increase of 11 per cent.
There was a decrease in prices in the textile industry (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of electric machines and instruments (0.3 per cent).
In the rest of the processing sectors, the pace of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 per cent.
Over the past year in the processing industry globally increased prices by 10.2 percent.
Electricity prices, gas, heat and water supply exceeded the previous year's prices by 18.7 percent.
In August, among the different sectors of domestic trade, the largest monthly price increase (0.7 per cent) was recorded in the investment goods sectors.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, in the energy sector and in the intermediate sectors there was no change compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, with respect to the same month of the previous year, the highest price increase occurred in the energy sectors and in the intermediate industry (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer commodity producing branches, a decline of 6.8 per cent was recorded and in investment goods of 1.4 per cent.
The export prices of the industry calculated in HUF increased by 1.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and compared to 12 months, there was a 3.9 per cent decrease.
The contribution of our national currency in one month was reduced by 1.7 per cent compared to the euro and by 7.1 per cent compared to the dollar, compared to August 2007 it strengthened by 7.5 per cent compared to the euro and 15.9 per cent compared to the dollar.
