Today the European Summit for Equal Opportunities was launched in Paris, its host is France, which is also the President of the European Union this year.
Livia Járóka, Member of the European People's Party for Fidesz, in her message addressed to the plenary, as one of the main speakers of this professional meeting, drew attention to the segregation in education, because it is one of the most serious violations that hit Roma children and is also the biggest obstacle to the rise of their interests.
This high-level conference was opened - on behalf of the French Presidency - by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs and Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner responsible for jobs, social affairs and equal opportunities.
