Járóka - according to the press bureau of the Fidesz group of deputies in the European Parliament - warned that in addition to discrimination in employment, Gypsies stay out of the labour market first because of their low level of schooling.
"Most Gypsy youth have not finished middle school and due to poor quality of basic education, only a negligible part can obtain university diploma."
Járóka also stressed that education, as a fundamental human right, has a decisive role in the establishment of other human rights as well.
Investment in early Roma children's education can strengthen the economy of EU Member States.
According to the Euro MP, there is a need to raise awareness of these issues widely among both Gypsies and non-gypsies.
For the sooner a Gypsy student begins school, the more possibilities he will have to become an active member of the labour market; through income and consumption taxes they will also contribute to the national budget.
"Gypsies, as citizens of the European Union, must be guaranteed the right to a quality education and to ensure the abolition of segregated and low-level education" – said Livia Járóka.
