Bruxel had asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, seeing the great use of portable musical devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise that this gives rise to.
"Scientists - the EU executive concludes - confirm that it is a matter of concern and the European Commission will now examine together with Member States and stakeholders what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable musical devices and related devices."
At present, there is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable musical devices to 100 dB, but concern increases as the auditory damage that can result from excessive exposure to such sources of noise.
It is possible to limit these damage much by using solutions such as reducing levels and noise exposure time.
In its opinion, the Ue Scientific Committee points out that users of portable musical devices listen loudly (more than 89 decibels) to music for only 5 hours a week exceed the current maximum permitted noise limit at the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for longer periods risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity after a period of 5 years.
It means that it affects 5-10% of users of such devices and the number can be quantified between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
