Goodbye to the old cinema Paradise, the cities cancel historic halls
Historical cinemas close favoring the Multiplexs.
"A city without cinematographic rooms in a blind city, is like a face without eyes."
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore effectively photographs what is happening in the major Italian urban centers and also in the provincial cities.
The process of marginalisation of cinemas, which with the birth of the great meticons on the periphery and the consequent disappearance of the mono-rooms in the central areas of the city, is an inevitable and indisputable event with all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear are almost always historical places, full of memory, "it is as if a friend died, a acquaintance with whom was shared a piece of place and so much emotion", observes the director of the new cinema Paradise, the film that twenty years ago won the cousin Oscar and the grand jury prize to Cannes, which counted the poetry of a provincial cinema and the nostalgia for the way to live the cinema that perhaps lost forever.
The figures given by the Anec, the main association of traders, speak clearly: in the last five years they have closed 316 traditional cinemas, and to pay most of them are the halls of the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures are as first, Emilia-Romagna with 82 less cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
It is a demonstration that the person responsible for his disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, are own these three Italian regions that have made record the largest number of new methic cinemas: 195 screens more in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany than in Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian exercise has developed irrationally" notes Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, "it would be useful to build new structures but it would be necessary to guarantee the permanence of those already existing, because when a city hall closes, not all its frequenters are willing to transfer to the meticones.
Not to mention the lack of funds for traders: the previous debt of the state is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful from an ethical and moral point of view, that the government does not respect the laws that exist.
To support the sector would be between 16 and 18 million euros a year".
Interestingly, the case of Bologna, the first Italian city concerned with the closures, decided to repair itself with the signing of a protocol between the municipality and Anec, the first of this type in Italy to promote and protect the mono-sala cinema both in the historical center and in the periphery.
Among the rules provided for are tax facilitation measures for managers and public benefits in terms of mobility: viewers will be able to enter the restricted traffic zone and will have special parking rates.
"It's an initiative I like," observes Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by putting in place other measures.
It is true, that in contrast to the extra power of meticones, traditional rooms have to improve the quality of sound and image because the audience today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that was always important to me: the closure of Bagheria's cinema, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to perform the "New Paradise cinema", which I had been thinking for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass by the Rialto or the Quirinale of Via Nazionale already closed, where I have lived so many shared emotions, in order not to see the posters blackened by the dust, I turn to the other side".
